Wednesday night I learned firsthand that  bullets aren't always removed from gunshot victims. Crazy Story! After picking my gf up from the airport from a work trip we ran by my place to get her dog who I was watching. Within a matter of minutes, my car was  burglarized. Her backpack with her Macbook for work, a new Louis vuitton bag , her passport, her credit cards etc all gone.  I seen kids running away and knew right away it was them. I made her wait and hopped in my car chasing them down an alley, right as I was getting out a kid starts shooting. Luckily he couldn't shoot for shit or I might not be making this post. Couple shots whizzed by, one hit my whip, and I got hit in the side of the leg.  Usually I always have my weapon on me but left it at home, which is good for him cuz he probably wouldn't be breathing today. After I was hit i still tailed the kid but fell back a bit, not much I could really do without my gun. I went back to where my gf was and by then cops and paramedics showed up. My GF was able to track her computer which we could see was on the move so we coordinated with the officers who sent cops looking for the kids. They musta got spooked and dropped her bag. She was able to get all her things back thankfully. After the paramedics looked at my leg, which they said it was just a graze 😂, but i was told by an officer to go to tbe hospital. So we went to the hospital , they took X-rays and found the bullet still lodged in my leg. Like I said above apparently they dont remove bullets in a lot of cases so its gonna be chillin in my leg for a bit. Looking back on things, it really wasn't a good idea chasing them but it was a reaction and I'd probably do the same thing 10/10 times. The biggest lessons I took from this is never assume things. I chased them thinking they were just kids stealing not thinking they'd have a weapon. Also I will NEVER leave my place without my 🔫 again. Its my right and I will damn sure be exercising it. I'm in a little pain but honestly fine, walking around just with a slight limp. Gonna rest a bit but I'll be training tonight.💪🏽 Make sure you guys stay vigilant and stay safe out here!

FUCK YEA!!!
-
Been exactly a week since I got shot. Bullet still lodged in my leg and all. To be honest i didn't think things would be moving this fast but I'm healing up extremely quick. Leg gets sore at times but im not even limping anymore. I'll be back training legs later this week after this actually. 
-
This video was completely unplanned but the last few days I been waking up in bit of a funk , a little unmotivated to do anything honestly. So after this I mighta got a little emotional but also I'm pumped AF now. 
-
Some say I'm lucky but I say Im blessed beyond measure. Things could have been much worse. Like i said I'm extremely excited, now my goal is to get on stage before the years over. Big thank you to everyone who reached out to me, I can't tell you how much it meant to me to have so many people message me and actually care. I appreciate you all! 
-
Also for the record, I haven't sprinted or ran in at least 10 years😂🙈 
Now its time to work! 💪🏽

Tomorrow will be one week since having this removed from my leg. What exactly? A 9 mm Hollow point round thats been there for about 3 months. If you're lost, check the first post pinned on my page for details. 
-
After the incident I was shocked how fast I healed up. Within a few weeks i was back training legs and it was as if nothing happened. That suddenly changed however as i started getting bothered by my leg. A few times I woke up sore, swollen , and it hurt to put weight on my leg. After discussing this with my primary physician he agreed it was best to remove the bullet which I'm thankful for.
-
As far as competing, i was hoping to get back on stage later this year but after this whole incident it looks like I'll be sitting this year out.  With only a few years left in my bodybuilding career I want to make the most of my final appearances and with the amount of time I've had to miss in the gym thats not possible.  After my recovery I'll be back training nonstop and looking forward to preparing for next year.
